# PID and Bias Boundaries

## Personally Identifiable Data

Real names and identifiers MUST be anonymized everywhere — code, config, state, documentation.

| Real     | Anonymized                      |
| -------- | ------------------------------- |
| Garrett  | PARTICIPANT 1 / `participant_1` |
| Sasha    | PARTICIPANT 2 / `participant_2` |
| Harrison | PARTICIPANT 3 / `participant_3` |
| Tucker   | PET / `pet`                     |

Use `PARTICIPANT N` in documentation (CLAUDE.md). Use `participant_n` in code and data files.

If you encounter a new real name, flag it — do not guess the substitution.

## Platform-Neutral Language

Prefer capability-first language in product descriptions, user-facing explanations, and architecture narratives. When documenting actual implementation dependencies, provider APIs, environment variables, or webhook behavior, use the real product name where precision matters.

| Avoid                   | Use instead                           |
| ----------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| iPhone                  | PHONE                                 |
| thumbs up / thumbs down | positive reaction / negative reaction |
| text messages           | phone-native messages                 |
| phone number            | messaging identity                    |
| screenshot              | image                                 |
| JSON files              | configuration store / state store     |

## Why

These boundaries exist so the system design remains portable, unbiased, and safe to share. Every piece of content — documentation, types, data — must pass through these filters.
